    <p><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a></p>

    <h1>Old Traf&#xAD;ford ready to be a Theatre of Dreams again</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <time datetime="2021-01-14"><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210114/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-14">2021-01-14</a></time> -
        David Lee davi&#xAD;dlee@sph.com.sg

            <a href="/category/tag-268435472/en/sg">Sports</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268436979/en/sg">Soccer</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268490325/en/sg">Premier League (England)</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-539122846/en/sg">Old Trafford</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537084843/en/sg">Manchester United F.C.</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068967/en/sg">Manchester</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537641567/en/sg">Burnley F.C.</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537260605/en/sg">Liverpool Football Club</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068965/en/sg">Liverpool</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537251011/en/sg">Arsenal F.C.</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-541027411/en/sg">Ole Gunnar Solskj&#xE6;r</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537725516/en/sg">David de Gea</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-538280358/en/sg">Luke Shaw</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540434413/en/sg">Marcus Rashford</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-538603521/en/sg">Anthony Martial</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540434419/en/sg">Harry Maguire</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537259591/en/sg">Cristiano Ronaldo</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537192423/en/sg">Robin van Persie</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540434929/en/sg">Bruno Miguel Borges Fernandes</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-538067823/en/sg">Paul Pogba</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068131/en/sg">France</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537663027/en/sg">France national football team</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537242034/en/sg">Aston Villa Football Club</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068956/en/sg">Birmingham (England)</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537965216/en/sg">Brighton &amp; Hove Albion F.C.</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537277350/en/sg">Manchester City Football Club</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-539251004/en/sg">Virgil van Dijk</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-538852065/en/sg">Joe Gomez</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-541022723/en/sg">Diogo Jota</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-538570227/en/sg">Thiago Alc&#xE2;ntara</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540434658/en/sg">Sadio Man&#xE9;</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537979995/en/sg">Mohamed Salah</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537543961/en/sg">Sergio Ag&#xFC;ero</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540433967/en/sg">Fernandinho</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540599282/en/sg">Scott McTominay</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537511353/en/sg">&#xC9;ric Cantona</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537189387/en/sg">Wayne Rooney</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537697189/en/sg">Joel Matip</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-539252007/en/sg">Benjamin Mendy</a>     </section>

        <p>It has been 1,221 days since Manch­ester United were last top of the English Premier League (EPL). On Tues­day, they reached the sum­mit again by win­ning 1-0 at Burn­ley to knock cham­pi­ons Liver­pool off the perch.</p>
        <p>No tro­phies are handed out for top­ping the league mid-sea­son, but it re­mains an achieve­ment for a team that were lan­guish­ing in 15th with just seven points from their first six games af­ter be­ing beaten 1-0 by Arse­nal on Nov 2.</p>
        <p>Since then, United have claimed 29 points out of a pos­si­ble 33 – more than any other top-flight team. These are the five fac­tors be­hind their turn­around.</p>
        <p>FAITH</p>
        <p>The run­ning joke is that United al­ways de­liver re­sults when Ole</p>
        <p>Gun­nar Sol­sk­jaer is on the brink of get­ting fired. It hap­pened last Jan­uary when they lost to Liver­pool and Burn­ley and went on a 14-match un­beaten run to fin­ish third, and in Novem­ber when they lost to Arse­nal and Is­tan­bul Basak­se­hir in the Cham­pi­ons League be­fore their cur­rent 11-match EPL streak. But ri­val fans won’t be laugh­ing now.</p>
        <p>The own­ers and United board should be cred­ited for not suc­cumb­ing to pres­sure to sack Sol­sk­jaer. Given time, the Nor­we­gian has im­posed his phi­los­o­phy and per­son­al­ity on the team. And he in turn has paid the faith for­ward, stick­ing with goal­keeper David de Gea. This has paid div­i­dends – the Spa­niard re­placed high-pro­file blun­ders with blind­ing saves in re­cent matches.</p>
        <p>Play­ers such as Luke Shaw, Scott Mc­Tom­i­nay, Mar­cus Rash­ford and An­thony Mar­tial have im­proved un­der his tute­lage, and he also stood by Harry Maguire de­spite the de­fender’s as­sault con­vic­tion and con­cerns over his form.</p>
        <p>FER­NAN­DES</p>
        <p>Every cham­pi­onship-win­ning team have an at­tack­ing tal­is­man with charis­matic lead­er­ship. For United, it was Eric Can­tona in the 1990s; Wayne Rooney and Cris­tiano Ron­aldo took com­mand af­ter the mil­len­nium; and in their last ti­tle tri­umph in 2013, it was Robin van Per­sie. But there has been a dearth of such in­spi­ra­tional fig­ures at Old Traf­ford since then.</p>
        <p>En­ter Bruno Fer­nan­des, who has al­most sin­gle-hand­edly dragged United out of the dol­drums. Rash­ford and Mar­tial are fine at­tack­ers in their own right who pro­duce in spurts, but the</p>
        <p>Por­tuguese mid­fielder’s ar­rival means there is some­one who can help the team tran­si­tion more flu­idly and ef­fec­tively from de­fence to at­tack con­sis­tently.</p>
        <p>There is a sem­blance of a counter-at­tack­ing iden­tity now, with method to Sol­sk­jaer’s mid­field se­lec­tion – Mc­Tom­i­nay and Fred in a dou­ble-pivot against more dan­ger­ous teams to break up play, and a more ad­ven­tur­ous di­a­mond with Paul Pogba af­forded free­dom on the left against smaller teams.</p>
        <p>Which­ever com­bi­na­tion he goes for, there is only one can­di­date as the at­tack­ing mid­fielder – Fer­nan­des. It is not just his vi­sion and tech­ni­cal abil­ity that led to his 19 goals and 14 as­sists in 31 league games since join­ing last Jan­uary. His un­yield­ing de­mand for ex­cel­lence has rubbed off on his team­mates and he is just the leader United have missed.</p>
        <p>FRENCH­MAN</p>
        <p>Pogba could have been that man. For €105 mil­lion (S$169.5 mil­lion), one would ex­pect the world’s most ex­pen­sive mid­fielder to be able to score, as­sist, tackle, and carry the team – what Fer­nan­des has been do­ing at half the price. In­stead, what United got for the most part was a sulk­ing, un­der­per­form­ing player.</p>
        <p>But the France in­ter­na­tional’s track record shows he is at his best when some­thing big is at stake. Cue the 2017 Eu­ropa League fi­nal and the 2018 World Cup fi­nal.</p>
        <p>He is show­ing sim­i­lar signs of life again, back­ing up his ex­cel­lent show­ing against As­ton Villa with a sump­tu­ous volleyed win­ner against Burn­ley.</p>
        <p>His re­cent en­thu­si­asm stands in stark con­trast with his early-sea­son form, which was em­bod­ied in the mind­less con­ces­sion of a penalty in the loss to Arse­nal.</p>
        <p>FOR­TUNE</p>
        <p>On the topic of penal­ties, many will point to United beat­ing Brighton 3-2 in Septem­ber thanks to one awarded by the VAR (video as­sis­tant ref­eree) af­ter the fi­nal whis­tle and put it down to the luck of the devil.</p>
        <p>Their main ri­vals – Liver­pool and Manch­ester City – have also been hit by Covid- and in­jury-en­forced ab­sences while Sol­sk­jaer’s men have re­mained rel­a­tively un­scathed.</p>
        <p>Liver­pool have likely lost key cen­tre-backs Vir­gil van Dijk and Joe Gomez for the en­tire sea­son with knee in­juries. The oth­ers who have pop­u­lated the physio’s room in­clude goal­keeper Alis­son, Joel Matip, Naby Keita and Diogo Jota. Those hit by Covid in­clude mid­fielder Thi­ago Al­can­tara, for­wards Sa­dio Mane and Mo­hamed Salah.</p>
        <p>City have had key play­ers Ser­gio Aguero, Fer­nand­inho and Ben­jamin Mendy side­lined.</p>
        <p>Com­par­a­tively, United have had only Alex Telles, Pogba and Facundo Pel­listri test­ing pos­i­tive so far, while hav­ing ad­e­quate cover.</p>
        <p>FIT­NESS</p>
        <p>While some at­tribute United’s com­par­a­tive lack of in­juries to for­tune, it may also be due to Sol­sk­jaer’s fit­ness reg­i­men. When he took over in late 2018, he in­tro­duced ex­tra train­ing and per­son­alised ses­sions to help his play­ers adapt to the high-press­ing game he wants.</p>
        <p>This su­pe­rior fit­ness has helped them score 10 of their 34 goals in the last 15 min­utes and mount six come-from-be­hind wins this term.</p>
        <p>No­body at United will en­ter­tain ti­tle talk now, but they have given them­selves a chance at con­tend­ing and Old Traf­ford is once again a Theatre of Dreams.</p>
        <p>The own­ers and United board should be cred­ited for not suc­cumb­ing to pres­sure to sack Sol­sk­jaer. Given time, the Nor­we­gian has im­posed his phi­los­o­phy and per­son­al­ity on the team.</p>

